    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I think this is actually the proper behavior, albeit unintuitive the first time you encounter it, and is consistent with the rest of the Python ecosystem.  The rule for rounding is that exact halfway cases are  rounded to the nearest even result.  This has a few advantages, for example, it's less prone to introducing positive or negative bias.  See the [Python 3.x rounding behavior](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10825926/python-3-x-rounding-behavior) question on Stack Overflow for more details.\r\n\r\nThis is indeed how pandas, numpy, and the standard library do rounding:\r\n```python\r\nIn [1]: import numpy as np; import pandas as pd; pd.__version__\r\nOut[1]: '0.25.0.dev0+85.g0eddba8'\r\n\r\nIn [2]: pd.Series([1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5]).round()\r\nOut[2]: \r\n0    2.0\r\n1    2.0\r\n2    4.0\r\n3    4.0\r\ndtype: float64\r\n\r\nIn [3]: np.array([1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5]).round()\r\nOut[3]: array([2., 2., 4., 4.])\r\n\r\nIn [4]: round(1.5), round(2.5), round(3.5), round(4.5)\r\nOut[4]: (2, 2, 4, 4)\r\n```\r\n\r\n"
